ads.title: Street Fever Basketball Arcade Machine Rare
ads.description: The Street Fever Basketball Arcade Machine by Ice is an original game featuring the popular Street Fever theme. With its original design and high-quality construction, this machine is a must-have for any arcade or gaming enthusiast looking to add a retro touch to their collection. Very Similar on Full Court Fever. Both games gives the player a moving hoop with a back and forth movement. Also the "Rotating" turntable that enables the player to shoot from every possible spot on the court. Game height is adjustable to either 8, 8.5 or 9 feet. Full Court Fever or Street Fever are also an accurate representation of basketball. We use a 7 inch ball and a 14 inch hoop so the proportions are correct. Has some minor scratches on the side, but works great.

Head-to-head format: The machine is a tabletop, or "cocktail," arcade cabinet, with two sets of controls facing each other. This allows two players to sit and compete directly across from one another.
STOOLS INCLYDED IN UNOPENED BOX BRAND NEW
Hardware and display: The table is equipped with a 17-inch color LCD screen and a protective, clear top to guard against spills and dust. It features two control panels with full-size joysticks and buttons for an authentic arcade feel. Two speakers, one on each side, provide audio with adjustable volume.
Stools: While some retailers offer packages that include matching stools, they are typically sold separately. Arcade1Up sells its own line of branded, height-adjustable stools with chrome legs and padded seats that are compatible with the table.

ads.author: Donald Hopkins
ads.title: Bally Spectrum Pinball - Restored & Rare
ads.description:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AWB92q7rrVQ

I purchased this game on 1/1/2023. It was meticulously restored by Frank W. in Alabama. Fully LED'ed. All of the playfield inserts were swapped to yoppsicles making this game a maintenance dream. No more flaky bulb sockets.

I installed an aftermarket squawk and talk board made by Jeff Klein. It is leaps and bounds better than the original.

Bally supposedly made about 900 of these in 1982. But if you listen to interviews of the guys who were there back in the day (Todd Tuckey & Alan Reisman), about 300 of these games were actually sold. Operators didn't want the Spectrum because it wasn't making much money. The gameplay was just too different back then so it didn't catch on. However, 43 years later... the very unusual rules, unique gameplay and rarity have made Bally Spectrum very sought after.

This is one of the finer examples of this game you will find for sale. Priced accordingly. No excuses or issues. Plug N play.

ads.author: Darren Cuda
ads.title: Atari Gauntlet 2 player arcade game
ads.description: Atari's Gauntlet (1985) was famous for its 4-player arcade cabinet, but a dedicated 2-player version was released by Atari Games in 1986, alongside its sequel, Gauntlet II, offering players choices between the Warrior, Valkyrie, Elf, and Wizard for cooperative dungeon crawling. Both games featured top-down fantasy action with hordes of monsters, treasure, and the iconic announcer, with Gauntlet II introducing more mazes and character choice flexibility.

ads.author: Rob LaDue
ads.title: üòç‚ù§Ô∏è‚ò†Ô∏è Black Rose Pinball Machine - Pirate Themed
ads.description:
\ud83d\ude0d\u2764\ufe0f\u2764\ufe0f Gorgeous Black Rose Pinball Machine \u2694\ufe0f\u2620\ufe0f\ud83e\ude93 -Pirate Themed

This beautiful Black Rose, pirate-themed\u2620\ufe0f, pinball machine was produced in 1992 and features many unique game elements, including a pop-up twisting cannon shot to sink ships and shoot bonus shots, video-mode bonus games (uses the flippers to play a Knife Throwing, Walk-the-Plank, and Swing-from-the-Rigging analog video game), Easter-egg bonuses for trick shots, treasure bonuses, parrot bonus, etc. Play is flawless!  All plastics and metals are in great condition, and the lights, cannon, analog display, 3 flippers, plunger, sound, and ball eject perform perfectly. Complete Operations Manual included.

This machine has been lovingly used for home play since our purchase of it in 2008.  We are a smoke free home. At the time of purchase, the machine had been completely shopped, including replacing many of the older incandescent lighting with LEDs.  Some of the incandescent lights were retained to provide some of that old school pinball feel.  All rubbers were replaced last year, a pinball specialist gave it a once over in December 2024, and the field was recently rewaxed.  The cabinet and playfield are near flawless and the legs are free of rust.

Before being returned to the States for its reshop in 2007, this machine was exported to Italy.  It retains its original Italian lire coin return buttons. The game speaks and displays English (go figure!\ud83d\ude06). The coin change box was missing when we acquired it, but is easily found on the internet.

For an older (and more affordable) pinball game, Black Rose has so-ooo many different and unique elements and shots, that our family never got tired of it (our moving necessitates the sale).  The pirate theme is exciting for both adults and children too and for those that desire, the game can be upgraded with the Skull and Bones kit, which changes the game in many interesting ways.

Please message me with any questions and I will do the best I can to answer them.  Play tests can also be arranged (located in Bradenton, FL).  Shipping must be arranged by the buyer.  

Beautiful machine! \u2620\ufe0f\u2764\ufe0f Thanks!

Hi! 

I own and operate arcade games like mini claw machines, cut 2 win games, etc. I am based out of enterprise

I place these machines in restaurants, play places, gyms, and more. Then of course pay the locations a commission on all plays. 

There is no cost to the locations, they just get paid a healthy commission. Great way to make money on unused space, as well as generate an entirely new draw to your establishment.

I would love to come some time and talk to you guys about getting one in y\u2019all\u2019s location. You would be amazed how many people continue to come back to some of my locations strictly to grab some food and play my claw machines.

My smallest claw machine only takes up 12 inches of floor space, and uses less than $5 per month of electricity!
